teinising hormone acts on Sertoli cells to support sperm development","Follicle stimulating hormone directly stimulates sperm cell division","Testosterone acts directly on seminiferous tubules to maintain spermatogenesis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETestosterone acts directly on seminiferous tubules\u003C/strong\u003E through local diffusion from nearby Leydig cells, maintaining the high intratesticular concentrations necessary for spermatogenesis. This local action is essential as systemic testosterone levels are much lower.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone directly stimulates sperm cell division\u003C/strong\u003E - FSH acts on Sertoli cells rather than directly on developing sperm cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELuteinising hormone acts on Sertoli cells\u003C/strong\u003E - LH acts on Leydig cells to produce testosterone, not on Sertoli cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibin stimulates the release of gonadotrophin releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E - Inhibin provides negative feedback to suppress FSH release\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETestosterone primarily acts via the systemic circulation\u003C/strong\u003E - The systemic circulation does not provide the high local concentrations required for effective sperm production. Therefore, the critical action of testosterone is local, not systemic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe maintenance of spermatogenesis requires both FSH acting on Sertoli cells and high local concentrations of testosterone produced by Leydig cells in response to LH stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Follicle stimulating hormone stimulates Sertoli cells to support spermatogenesis and produce androgen binding protein.","Luteinising hormone stimulates Leydig cells to produce testosterone which is essential for spermatogenesis.","Testosterone acts locally in high concentrations within seminiferous tubules to maintain sperm production."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T21:55:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T21:57:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79805"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships